## Workflow : feature_dev_review_fix_dual
## Objectif : Developpement d'une nouvelle feature (plan + implement) suivi
## d'une review structuree dual verdict (Claude + GPT) avec boucle de
## correction automatique.
##
## Specialisation : projet carto (TypeScript CLI, pnpm, devbox).
##   - Build gate : devbox run -- pnpm typecheck && lint && test
##   - Tous les agents savent qu'ils doivent prefixer les commandes avec devbox.
##
## Repartition des roles :
##   - Claude Code = WORKER PRINCIPAL. Il fait tout le travail lourd :
##     planification, implementation, review primaire, verdict primaire,
##     correction de ses propres blockers.
##   - GPT (claw direct API, openai/gpt-5.4-mini) + Opus (claude_code) =
##     SUPPORT. N'interviennent QU'APRES approbation par Claude principal :
##       1. gpt_reviewer + gpt_verdict : second avis de verdict final
##          (cross-review pour attraper les angles morts du modele Claude
##          principal). Sans outils — review depuis le contexte fourni.
##       2. opus_fixer : si gpt_verdict rejette, opus_fixer (claude_code +
##          claude-opus-4-7) corrige UNIQUEMENT les blockers trouves par
##          gpt_reviewer. Le couple GPT/Opus ne touche jamais aux blockers
##          trouves par le Claude principal.
##   Si GPT approuve -> done. S'il rejette, opus_fixer corrige ce que
##   gpt_reviewer a trouve puis on repasse par la chaine Claude (review +
##   verdict) pour valider que la correction ne regresse rien. Claude reste
##   l'arbitre final de la qualite du code ; le couple GPT/Opus est un filet
##   de securite.
##
## Architecture :
##   [main] planner (claude)
##     -> [main] developer (inherit planner)
##        -> commit_namer_post_dev -> commit_post_dev (git commit WIP)
##        -> build_check_post_dev
##        -> [main] context_builder -> [main] reviewer (claude)
##           -> build_check -> [main] verdict (claude)
##             ^                                                         |
##             |                      not approved -> [main] claude_fixer-+
##             |                                                         |
##             |                     approved -> [support] gpt_reviewer
##             |                                           |
##             |                                 -> [support] gpt_verdict
##             |                                                     |
##             |                                       approved -> done
##             |                                                     |
##             |                      not approved -> [support] opus_fixer -+
##             |                                                             |
##             |                commit_namer_post_fix <---------------------+
##             |                         |
##             |                commit_post_fix (git commit WIP)
##             |                         |
##             +------------------ build_check_post_fix <-------------------+
##
##   Nouveautes vs pr_review_fix_dual :
##     - Phase amont "plan -> implement" qui cree le code a reviewer
##     - planner en readonly, developer inherit planner (context gratuit)
##     - Commits WIP reguliers :
##         * apres developer   (commit initial de la feature)
##         * apres claude_fixer (commit: fix reviews de Claude)
##         * apres opus_fixer  (commit: fix reviews de GPT)
##       Les commits se font AVANT le build check pour ne jamais perdre de
##       travail meme si la build casse (pattern rust_to_go_port).
##     - build_check_post_dev : gate deterministe apres le commit initial
##       (si le build casse, on repart du reviewer qui le verra, mais on a
##        deja capture l'erreur dans les logs ET un commit existe dans git)
##
## Primitives exercees : agent, judge, tool, done, fail, boucle bornee, publish,
##   session fresh/inherit, multi-backend (claude_code + claw direct API).
##
## Usage :
##   iterion run examples/feature_dev_review_fix_dual.iter \
##     --var workspace_dir=/Users/Vidy/code/dnum/iterion_carto/carto \
##     --var feature_title="Exhaustive CLI --help + README Getting Started" \
##     --var feature_description="See carto/plans/cli-docs-and-readme-refresh.md" \
##     --var acceptance_criteria="Every carto command/subcommand has a complete --help; README leads with Getting Started; env var precedence documented" \
##     --var base_ref=HEAD \
##     --store-dir .iterion \
##     --log-level info

vars:
  workspace_dir: string = "${PROJECT_DIR}"

## ─── Prompts : Phase dev ────────────────────────────────────────

prompt planner_system:
  You are a senior software architect writing an implementation plan
  for a new feature in the carto TypeScript CLI project. You explore
  the codebase (read-only) and produce a concrete, ordered, testable
  plan that another agent can execute.

  Project conventions (carto):
  - Every shell command must be prefixed with `devbox run --`
    (e.g. `devbox run -- pnpm test`, `devbox run -- node src/cli.ts --help`).
    Bare `pnpm` / `node` / `tsc` will fail.
  - Long logs go to stderr, machine output goes to stdout.
  - TypeScript (Node >= 24), ESM, Commander CLI, zod schemas.
  - Column registry in carto.columns.yaml is YAML-driven, no TS needed for new columns.

  Rules:
  - Plan ONLY the requested feature. Do not expand scope.
  - Cite file paths and symbols for every step (file:line where useful).
  - Identify existing patterns to follow and dependencies to reuse.
  - Flag risks, unknowns, and explicit non-goals.
  - Order steps so that each step leaves the workspace in a buildable state.

prompt planner_user:
  Produce an implementation plan for this feature.

  Feature title:
  {{input.feature_title}}

  Feature description:
  {{input.feature_description}}

  Acceptance criteria:
  {{input.acceptance_criteria}}

  Instructions:
  1. Explore the codebase to understand the existing architecture and patterns.
  2. Identify the files to create or modify with file:line references.
  3. Produce an ordered list of steps. Each step must be concrete and scoped.
  4. Note test additions/updates required for the acceptance criteria.
  5. List risks and non-goals explicitly.

prompt developer_system:
  You are a feature implementation agent working on the carto TypeScript
  CLI project. A planner has just explored the codebase in your session
  and produced a plan. Execute the plan.

  Project conventions (carto):
  - Every shell command must be prefixed with `devbox run --`.
    Verification commands: `devbox run -- pnpm typecheck`,
    `devbox run -- pnpm lint`, `devbox run -- pnpm test`.
    Running the CLI: `devbox run -- pnpm carto <cmd>`.
  - Node >= 24, TypeScript ESM, Commander.js for CLI, zod for schemas.
  - Long logs to stderr, machine output to stdout.
  - Tests use node:test (`node --test`). Test files: `test/**/*.test.ts`.

  Rules:
  - Apply the plan step by step. After each step, re-read the touched files.
  - Do not expand scope beyond the plan. If you find an issue outside scope,
    note it in remaining_work but do not fix it.
  - Follow existing patterns observed by the planner.
  - Add or update tests per the plan.
  - Before finishing, run `devbox run -- pnpm typecheck` and fix any TS errors.
  - Produce a structured summary of what was changed and what remains.

prompt developer_user:
  Implement the feature according to this plan.

  Feature title:
  {{input.feature_title}}

  Feature description:
  {{input.feature_description}}

  Acceptance criteria:
  {{input.acceptance_criteria}}

  Plan:
  {{input.plan}}

  Apply the plan now and produce a structured implementation report.

## ─── Prompts : Phase review (identiques a pr_review_fix_dual) ───

prompt context_builder_system:
  You are a PR context builder.
  Read the git diff between base and head, list changed files,
  identify the PR's purpose from commit messages, and flag risky areas
  (concurrency, security, error handling, database queries).
  Be factual and exhaustive. Do not editorialize.

prompt context_builder_user:
  Build a structured PR context.

  Base ref: {{vars.base_ref}}
  Head ref: {{vars.head_ref}}

  Feature being implemented:
  Title: {{vars.feature_title}}
  Description: {{vars.feature_description}}
  Acceptance criteria: {{vars.acceptance_criteria}}

  Developer report:
  {{input.dev_report}}

  Instructions:
  1. Run git diff between base and head
  2. List all changed files with their change type (added/modified/deleted)
  3. Cross-check the developer report against the actual diff
  4. Identify risky areas (concurrency, security, error handling, database)
  5. Summarize changes by domain/package

prompt reviewer_system:
  You are a senior code reviewer. You combine TWO roles:

  1. REVIEWER: evaluate code quality, error handling, idiomatic patterns,
     security, correctness, and whether the acceptance criteria are met.
     For each issue, cite file:line and classify as:
     - BLOCKER: would break production, cause data loss/corruption, or
       leave an acceptance criterion unmet
     - SUGGESTION: style, naming, cosmetic, non-critical improvements

  2. FIX PLANNER: if approved=false, produce a concrete, actionable fix_plan
     targeting ONLY blockers. Each step must specify the file, the line range,
     and the exact change to make.

  BLOCKER classification — these are ALWAYS blockers, not suggestions:
  - ACCEPTANCE CRITERIA NOT MET: any criterion left partially or unimplemented
  - TYPE ERRORS: `tsc --noEmit` must pass; any `as any` added without explicit
    justification, or any use of `@ts-ignore` / `@ts-expect-error` without
    comment justifying why
  - UNHANDLED PROMISE REJECTIONS: awaited async errors silently dropped,
    floating promises (missing `await` or `.catch`), fire-and-forget I/O
  - MISSING ERROR HANDLING: errors from fs, git, network, or SDK calls
    silently discarded
  - SECURITY: credential exposure (logged tokens, API keys in URLs),
    missing input validation on external inputs, shell-injection via
    unescaped user data in exec/spawn
  - OUTPUT CHANNEL VIOLATIONS: progress/log text written to stdout instead
    of stderr (breaks the "stderr=logs / stdout=machine output" contract)
  - BROKEN HELP: Commander commands/options missing `.description()` when
    acceptance criteria require exhaustive `--help`
  - HARDCODED CONFIG: values that should come from env vars or config files
    hardcoded at call sites

  SUGGESTION classification — these are NEVER blockers:
  - Code style, naming conventions, comment quality
  - Log level choices
  - Non-critical performance optimizations
  - Missing JSDoc
  - Deprecation warnings, backward compatibility concerns

  Rules:
  - approved=true means ZERO blockers AND all acceptance criteria met
  - When in doubt between BLOCKER and SUGGESTION, choose BLOCKER
  - Be factual: no compliments, no filler
  - If typecheck/lint/test failed, those are automatic blockers
  - Read the FULL file for each issue, not just the diff

prompt reviewer_user:
  Review this feature implementation.

  Review rules:
  {{input.review_rules}}

  Acceptance criteria:
  {{input.acceptance_criteria}}

  PR context:
  {{input.pr_context}}

  Build/lint results:
  {{input.build_check_results}}

  Previous verdict from primary reviewer:
  {{input.previous_claude_verdict}}

  Previous verdict from cross-reviewer:
  {{input.previous_gpt_verdict}}

  Previous fix summary (what the fixer did, including any false positives noted):
  {{input.previous_fix_summary}}

  For each changed file:
  1. Read the diff and the full file
  2. Identify concrete issues with file:line
  3. Classify each as BLOCKER or SUGGESTION
  4. Verify that each acceptance criterion is met
  5. If approved=false, produce an actionable fix_plan targeting blockers only

prompt verdict_system:
  You are the final judge of this review iteration.

  DECISION RULES:
  1. Any build/lint failure -> approved=false
  2. Any BLOCKER in the review -> approved=false
  3. Any acceptance criterion unmet -> approved=false
  4. Only SUGGESTIONS remaining AND all criteria met -> approved=true

  TRUST THE REVIEWER'S CLASSIFICATION. Do NOT reclassify a BLOCKER as a
  suggestion unless you can demonstrate with specific reasoning that the
  reviewer made a factual error.

  STAGNATION DETECTION: compare with previous_verdict. If the EXACT same
  blockers appear across iterations, note this in the executive_summary.
  Do NOT auto-approve — the workflow will fail and a human will decide.

prompt verdict_user:
  Evaluate this review and produce a verdict.

  Review:
  {{input.review}}

  Build/lint results:
  {{input.build_check_results}}

  Review rules:
  {{input.review_rules}}

  Previous verdict (empty on first iteration):
  {{input.previous_verdict}}

  Produce:
  1. A verdict (approved=true/false)
  2. List of remaining blockers
  3. List of suggestions
  4. Executive summary (3-5 lines for the feature author)

prompt gpt_reviewer_system:
  You are an independent code reviewer providing a second opinion.
  A first reviewer has already approved this feature implementation.
  Your job is to catch anything the first reviewer may have missed.

  Use the SAME blocker classification rules, including:
  - "acceptance criterion unmet" as a blocker
  - TypeScript type errors, unhandled promise rejections, missing error
    handling, security issues, stderr/stdout channel violations, broken
    Commander `--help` descriptions, hardcoded config.

  Be independent: do not rubber-stamp the first review. Read the actual code.
  If you find new blockers, produce a fix_plan.

  CRITICAL — SELF-CRITIQUE before classifying a BLOCKER:
  For EACH potential blocker, ask yourself:
  1. Am I reading the code correctly? Did I miss a guard nearby?
  2. Is this actually reachable in production, or dead code?
  3. Is the first reviewer right to NOT flag this?
  Only classify as BLOCKER if confident after this self-check.
  False positives waste entire fix loop iterations.

  Note: this reviewer runs via claw direct API and has no shell tool
  access. Form your verdict from the structured input only (PR context,
  changed-file list, risky areas, acceptance criteria, primary reviewer's
  findings). Do not invent file contents — if a claim cannot be verified
  from the input, surface it as a question or a soft suggestion rather
  than a blocker.

prompt gpt_reviewer_user:
  Provide an independent second review.

  Review rules:
  {{input.review_rules}}

  Acceptance criteria:
  {{input.acceptance_criteria}}

  PR context:
  {{input.pr_context}}

  Build/lint results:
  {{input.build_check_results}}

  First reviewer's assessment:
  {{input.claude_verdict}}

  Previous cross-review verdict (for stagnation awareness):
  {{input.previous_gpt_verdict}}

  Instructions:
  1. Read the critical files yourself
  2. Focus on areas the first reviewer may have overlooked
  3. Verify acceptance criteria independently
  4. Classify issues as BLOCKER or SUGGESTION
  5. If approved=false, produce a fix_plan for the new blockers

## ─── Prompts : Commit ──────────────────────────────────────────

prompt commit_namer_system:
  You generate semantic commit messages for work just completed on the
  carto project. You receive a structured description of what changed
  and produce a single-line conventional commit message.

  Format: type(scope): description
  Types:
    - feat     : new user-facing capability
    - fix      : bug fix or review-blocker resolution
    - refactor : code restructuring without behavior change
    - test     : test-only changes
    - docs     : documentation only (README, --help, comments)
    - chore    : tooling, config, dependencies
  Scope (pick the most affected area; keep short):
    - cli, grist, inspect, secrets, columns, git, llm, config, docs
  Description:
    - Imperative mood ("add X", not "added X")
    - Under 72 characters
    - Specific: "fix(grist): retry 429 on auto-ia-run" not "fix grist"

  SHELL SAFETY RULES (IMPORTANT):
    - Do NOT include single quotes (') in the message
    - Do NOT include double quotes (") in the message
    - Do NOT include backticks (`) in the message
    - Do NOT include newlines — single line only
  The message is interpolated into a shell command. Any of these characters
  will break the commit. Use plain prose only.

prompt commit_namer_user:
  Produce a commit message for the work just completed.

  Change type (dev / claude-fix / opus-fix): {{input.change_type}}

  Summary of work:
  {{input.summary}}

  Files changed:
  {{input.files_changed}}

  Produce type, scope, description, and full_message. The full_message must
  follow the format "type(scope): description" and respect the shell safety
  rules. No quotes, no backticks, no newlines.

prompt fixer_system:
  You are in a code review session for the carto TypeScript CLI project.
  A reviewer has identified problems and you have access to their full
  session context. EXECUTE the fix plan.

  Project conventions (carto):
  - Every shell command must be prefixed with `devbox run --`.
    Bare `pnpm` / `node` / `tsc` will fail.
  - Verification: `devbox run -- pnpm typecheck`,
    `devbox run -- pnpm lint`, `devbox run -- pnpm test`.

  Rules:
  - Apply corrections methodically, one by one
  - After each fix, re-read the file to verify correctness
  - Only fix what the plan specifies - do not refactor beyond scope
  - If a fix would break something else, note it in summary but still apply
  - If a blocker turns out to be a false positive after reading the code,
    note it clearly in summary (e.g. "B2 is a false positive because...")
  - Before finishing, run `devbox run -- pnpm typecheck` on the workspace.

prompt fixer_user:
  Execute the following fix plan.

  Fix plan:
  {{input.fix_plan}}

  Review rules:
  {{input.review_rules}}

  Apply the corrections and verify the rules are satisfied.

## ─── Schemas ────────────────────────────────────────────────────

schema feature_request:
  feature_title: string
  feature_description: string
  acceptance_criteria: string

schema plan_output:
  summary: string
  ordered_steps: string[]
  files_to_create: string[]
  files_to_modify: string[]
  tests_required: string[]
  risks: string[]
  non_goals: string[]

schema dev_input:
  feature_title: string
  feature_description: string
  acceptance_criteria: string
  plan: json

schema dev_output:
  summary: string
  files_changed: string[]
  commands_run: string[]
  tests_run: string[]
  remaining_work: string[]

schema pr_context_request:
  base_ref: string
  head_ref: string
  dev_report: json

schema pr_context:
  pr_title: string
  pr_description: string
  changed_files: string[]
  summary: string
  risky_areas: string[]

schema review_request:
  pr_context: json
  review_rules: string
  acceptance_criteria: string
  build_check_results: string
  previous_claude_verdict: string
  previous_gpt_verdict: string
  previous_fix_summary: string

schema review_result:
  summary: string
  blockers: string[]
  suggestions: string[]
  files_reviewed: string[]
  approved: bool
  fix_plan: string
  confidence: string [enum: "low", "medium", "high"]

schema check_input:
  workspace_dir: string

schema check_result:
  passed: bool
  exit_code: int
  logs: string

schema verdict_request:
  review: json
  build_check_results: json
  review_rules: string
  previous_verdict: string

schema verdict_result:
  approved: bool
  blockers: string[]
  suggestions: string[]
  executive_summary: string
  confidence: string [enum: "low", "medium", "high"]

schema gpt_review_request:
  pr_context: json
  review_rules: string
  acceptance_criteria: string
  build_check_results: json
  claude_verdict: json
  previous_gpt_verdict: string

schema fix_input:
  fix_plan: string
  review_rules: string

schema fix_output:
  applied: bool
  summary: string
  files_changed: string[]

schema commit_context_input:
  change_type: string
  summary: string
  files_changed: string[]

schema commit_name_output:
  type: string [enum: "feat", "fix", "refactor", "test", "docs", "chore"]
  scope: string
  description: string
  full_message: string

schema commit_tool_input:
  workspace_dir: string
  full_message: string

schema commit_result:
  success: bool
  output: string

## ─── Nodes : Phase dev [MAIN = Claude Code] ─────────────────────

agent planner:
  backend: "claude_code"
  input: feature_request
  output: plan_output
  publish: plan
  system: planner_system
  user: planner_user
  session: fresh
  tools: [Bash, Read, Glob, Grep]
  tool_max_steps: 20
  readonly: true
  reasoning_effort: high

agent developer:
  backend: "claude_code"
  input: dev_input
  output: dev_output
  publish: dev_report
  system: developer_system
  user: developer_user
  session: inherit
  tools: [Bash, Read, Edit, Write, Glob, Grep]
  tool_max_steps: 40
  reasoning_effort: high

## Commit namer after dev: generates a commit message from the developer's
## structured output (summary + files_changed). session: fresh + data-passing
## (not session: fork) because the same node is also reused in the fix path,
## which may come from a non-claude_code backend — fork across backends is unsafe.
agent commit_namer_post_dev:
  backend: "claude_code"
  input: commit_context_input
  output: commit_name_output
  system: commit_namer_system
  user: commit_namer_user
  session: fresh
  readonly: true
  reasoning_effort: high

## Commit the dev's work BEFORE the build check (WIP commit pattern from
## rust_to_go_port). If the build check fails afterwards, the work is
## preserved and the fix loop can iterate. git commit is skipped if nothing
## was staged (no-op safe).
tool commit_post_dev:
  command: "devbox run -- git -C {{input.workspace_dir}} add -A && devbox run -- git -C {{input.workspace_dir}} diff --cached --quiet || devbox run -- git -C {{input.workspace_dir}} commit -m {{input.full_message}}"
  input: commit_tool_input
  output: commit_result

## Build check after dev: captures compile errors immediately.
## If it fails, the reviewer will see the failing build in its input
## and the fix loop will kick in naturally.
tool build_check_post_dev:
  command: "cd {{input.workspace_dir}} && devbox run -- pnpm typecheck && devbox run -- pnpm lint && devbox run -- pnpm test"
  input: check_input
  output: check_result

## ─── Nodes : Phase review primaire [MAIN = Claude Code] ─────────
## Toute la chaine de review primaire (+ fixer primaire) tourne sur
## claude_code. C'est Claude qui porte la qualite du code.

agent context_builder:
  backend: "claude_code"
  input: pr_context_request
  output: pr_context
  publish: pr_context
  system: context_builder_system
  user: context_builder_user
  session: fresh
  tools: [Bash, Read, Glob, Grep]
  tool_max_steps: 15
  reasoning_effort: high

agent reviewer:
  backend: "claude_code"
  input: review_request
  output: review_result
  publish: claude_review
  system: reviewer_system
  user: reviewer_user
  session: fresh
  tools: [Bash, Read, Glob, Grep]
  tool_max_steps: 25
  readonly: true
  reasoning_effort: high

tool build_check:
  command: "cd {{input.workspace_dir}} && devbox run -- pnpm typecheck && devbox run -- pnpm lint && devbox run -- pnpm test"
  input: check_input
  output: check_result

judge verdict:
  backend: "claude_code"
  input: verdict_request
  output: verdict_result
  publish: claude_verdict
  system: verdict_system
  user: verdict_user
  session: fresh
  reasoning_effort: high

## ─── Nodes : Support final [SUPPORT = GPT + Opus] ───────────────
## Le filet de securite n'intervient QU'APRES approbation par Claude
## principal. Role strict :
##   1. gpt_reviewer / gpt_verdict : second avis final (claw direct API)
##   2. opus_fixer : corrige UNIQUEMENT les blockers trouves par
##      gpt_reviewer (claude_code + Opus, session fresh — inherit
##      n'est pas dispo car gpt_reviewer ne produit pas de session_id).
## Le couple GPT/Opus ne corrige jamais les blockers de Claude principal
## (claude_fixer s'en charge).

agent gpt_reviewer:
  ## Second-opinion reviewer via claw direct API (no shell tools);
  ## relies on the structured review request inputs for context.
  model: "openai/gpt-5.4-mini"
  input: gpt_review_request
  output: review_result
  publish: gpt_review
  system: gpt_reviewer_system
  user: gpt_reviewer_user
  readonly: true
  reasoning_effort: high

judge gpt_verdict:
  model: "openai/gpt-5.4-mini"
  input: verdict_request
  output: verdict_result
  publish: gpt_verdict
  system: verdict_system
  user: verdict_user
  reasoning_effort: high

agent claude_fixer:
  backend: "claude_code"
  input: fix_input
  output: fix_output
  publish: fix_report
  system: fixer_system
  user: fixer_user
  session: inherit
  tools: [Bash, Read, Edit, Write, Glob, Grep]
  tool_max_steps: 30
  reasoning_effort: high

agent opus_fixer:
  ## Fixer side runs claude_code with Opus to differentiate from the
  ## main claude_fixer (which uses claude_code's default model).
  ## Note: session: inherit no longer works here (the upstream gpt_reviewer
  ## now runs via claw direct API which has no session_id); use fresh.
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "claude-opus-4-7"
  input: fix_input
  output: fix_output
  publish: fix_report
  system: fixer_system
  user: fixer_user
  session: fresh
  tools: [Bash, Read, Edit, Write, Glob, Grep]
  tool_max_steps: 30
  reasoning_effort: high

## Commit namer after fix: shared between claude_fixer and opus_fixer.
## Two incoming edges (from either fixer) are OK because they are
## mutually exclusive in time (only one fixer runs per iteration).
agent commit_namer_post_fix:
  backend: "claude_code"
  input: commit_context_input
  output: commit_name_output
  system: commit_namer_system
  user: commit_namer_user
  session: fresh
  readonly: true
  reasoning_effort: high

tool commit_post_fix:
  command: "devbox run -- git -C {{input.workspace_dir}} add -A && devbox run -- git -C {{input.workspace_dir}} diff --cached --quiet || devbox run -- git -C {{input.workspace_dir}} commit -m {{input.full_message}}"
  input: commit_tool_input
  output: commit_result

tool build_check_post_fix:
  command: "cd {{input.workspace_dir}} && devbox run -- pnpm typecheck && devbox run -- pnpm lint && devbox run -- pnpm test"
  input: check_input
  output: check_result

## ─── Workflow ───────────────────────────────────────────────────

workflow feature_dev_review_fix_dual:
  vars:
    feature_title: string
    feature_description: string
    acceptance_criteria: string
    base_ref: string = "HEAD"
    head_ref: string = "HEAD"
    review_rules: string = "- Acceptance criteria fully implemented\n- `devbox run -- pnpm typecheck` passes (no new type errors, no unjustified `as any` or `@ts-ignore`)\n- `devbox run -- pnpm lint` passes\n- `devbox run -- pnpm test` passes\n- No swallowed errors, no floating promises, no fire-and-forget I/O\n- Proper error wrapping with context\n- No hardcoded secrets or credentials; config via env vars\n- stderr for logs, stdout for machine output (carto convention)\n- Every Commander command/option has a `.description()`\n- No dead code or unused imports"

  entry: planner

  budget:
    max_parallel_branches: 2
    max_duration: "3h"
    max_cost_usd: 75
    max_tokens: 8000000
    max_iterations: 60

  ## ═══ Phase 0 : Plan → Implement ═══════════════════════════════

  planner -> developer with {
    feature_title: "{{vars.feature_title}}",
    feature_description: "{{vars.feature_description}}",
    acceptance_criteria: "{{vars.acceptance_criteria}}",
    plan: "{{outputs.planner}}"
  }

  ## Commit the developer's work BEFORE the build check (WIP pattern).
  ## Even if typecheck/lint/test fails next, the work is preserved in git.
  developer -> commit_namer_post_dev with {
    change_type: "dev",
    summary: "{{outputs.developer.summary}}",
    files_changed: "{{outputs.developer.files_changed}}"
  }

  commit_namer_post_dev -> commit_post_dev with {
    workspace_dir: "{{vars.workspace_dir}}",
    full_message: "{{outputs.commit_namer_post_dev.full_message}}"
  }

  commit_post_dev -> build_check_post_dev with {
    workspace_dir: "{{vars.workspace_dir}}"
  }

  build_check_post_dev -> context_builder with {
    base_ref: "{{vars.base_ref}}",
    head_ref: "{{vars.head_ref}}",
    dev_report: "{{outputs.developer}}"
  }

  ## ═══ Phase 1 : Primary review -> build check -> verdict ═══════

  context_builder -> reviewer with {
    pr_context: "{{outputs.context_builder}}",
    review_rules: "{{vars.review_rules}}",
    acceptance_criteria: "{{vars.acceptance_criteria}}",
    build_check_results: "{{outputs.build_check_post_dev}}",
    previous_claude_verdict: "",
    previous_gpt_verdict: "",
    previous_fix_summary: ""
  }

  reviewer -> build_check with {
    workspace_dir: "{{vars.workspace_dir}}"
  }

  build_check -> verdict with {
    review: "{{outputs.reviewer}}",
    build_check_results: "{{outputs.build_check}}",
    review_rules: "{{vars.review_rules}}",
    previous_verdict: "{{outputs.verdict}}"
  }

  ## ═══ Phase 2 : Primary verdict routing ════════════════════════

  verdict -> gpt_reviewer when approved with {
    pr_context: "{{artifacts.pr_context}}",
    review_rules: "{{vars.review_rules}}",
    acceptance_criteria: "{{vars.acceptance_criteria}}",
    build_check_results: "{{outputs.build_check}}",
    claude_verdict: "{{outputs.verdict}}",
    previous_gpt_verdict: "{{outputs.gpt_verdict}}"
  }

  verdict -> claude_fixer when not approved as fix_loop(20) with {
    _session_id: "{{outputs.reviewer._session_id}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.reviewer.fix_plan}}",
    review_rules: "{{vars.review_rules}}"
  }

  verdict -> fail

  ## ═══ Phase 3 : Cross-review -> cross verdict ══════════════════

  gpt_reviewer -> gpt_verdict with {
    review: "{{outputs.gpt_reviewer}}",
    build_check_results: "{{outputs.build_check}}",
    review_rules: "{{vars.review_rules}}",
    previous_verdict: "{{outputs.gpt_verdict}}"
  }

  gpt_verdict -> done when approved

  ## GPT rejette -> opus_fixer corrige ce que gpt_reviewer a trouve
  ## (session inherit = fixer a deja lu les fichiers concernes).
  ## Claude ne touche pas a ces blockers : c'est GPT/Opus qui decide et corrige.
  gpt_verdict -> opus_fixer when not approved as fix_loop(20) with {
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.gpt_reviewer.fix_plan}}",
    review_rules: "{{vars.review_rules}}"
  }

  gpt_verdict -> fail

  ## ═══ Phase 4 : Post-fix verify, then back to reviewer ═════════

  ## Commit each fix BEFORE the build check, so every iteration leaves
  ## a trace in git (even if the build breaks and the loop retries).
  ## claude_fixer and opus_fixer both route to the shared commit_namer_post_fix;
  ## they are mutually exclusive in time (only one fires per iteration).
  claude_fixer -> commit_namer_post_fix with {
    change_type: "claude-fix",
    summary: "{{outputs.claude_fixer.summary}}",
    files_changed: "{{outputs.claude_fixer.files_changed}}"
  }

  opus_fixer -> commit_namer_post_fix with {
    change_type: "opus-fix",
    summary: "{{outputs.opus_fixer.summary}}",
    files_changed: "{{outputs.opus_fixer.files_changed}}"
  }

  commit_namer_post_fix -> commit_post_fix with {
    workspace_dir: "{{vars.workspace_dir}}",
    full_message: "{{outputs.commit_namer_post_fix.full_message}}"
  }

  commit_post_fix -> build_check_post_fix with {
    workspace_dir: "{{vars.workspace_dir}}"
  }

  build_check_post_fix -> reviewer as fix_loop(20) with {
    pr_context: "{{artifacts.pr_context}}",
    review_rules: "{{vars.review_rules}}",
    acceptance_criteria: "{{vars.acceptance_criteria}}",
    build_check_results: "{{outputs.build_check_post_fix}}",
    previous_claude_verdict: "{{outputs.verdict}}",
    previous_gpt_verdict: "{{outputs.gpt_verdict}}",
    previous_fix_summary: "{{artifacts.fix_report}}"
  }
